          "title": "The catechism of redemption — we were slaves",
          "body": "Verses 20-25 close the chapter with a parental script. When the son asks *what do these statutes mean?* the father does not answer with abstract ethics, philosophy of law, or moral principles. He answers with *story*: “We were slaves to Pharaoh in Egypt, and the LORD brought us out…” The catechism is fundamentally narrative-redemptive, not propositional. Obedience is grounded in remembered deliverance. Verse 23 captures the entire Exodus theology in one elegant clause: *He brought us out from there in order to bring us in*. Redemption has a destination; deliverance has a telos. The same logic anchors New Testament ethics — Paul never says “obey because it is the law” but “walk in a manner worthy of the calling with which you have been called” (Ephesians 4:1). The indicative of grace always precedes the imperative of obedience."
